lt",customRecommendationPrompt:null!=(t=this.Gt)&&t.customRecommendationPrompt?this.Kt:"Default"}},r.prototype.Jt=function(t,n,e,o){return(e=void 0===e?"":e)+"<skill_id='"+n+"'>\n        \t<skill_title>"+t.title+"</skill_title>        \t<skill_description>"+t.text+"</skill_description>\n        </skill>"+(void 0===o?"":o)},r.prototype.tn=function(){var t=null==(t=Object(o.get)().Custom)?void 0:t.parametricLauncher,t=null==t?void 0:t[this.nn];t?this.Gt=t:this.Kt&&(this.Gt=this.en[this.Kt])},r.prototype.rn=function(){this.Wt={summaryPrompt:'<instructions>\n\t1. Analyze the following webpage data to understand what the user is cognitively engaging with.\n\t2. Describe what is most cognitively relevant and focus only on what the user is reading, reacting to, or making decisions about.\n\t3. Include only the most relevant parts — what matters most about this page\'s purpose.\n\t4. Avoid layout or UI references (e.g., "left panel", "button on top").\n\t5. Include relevant names, apps, roles, emails, field labels, counts, IDs, expiration dates, or user-specific data.\n\t6. Keep it simple, sharp, and focused.\n\t7. Output ONLY string, maximum length of 100 words\n\t</instructions>\n\t<input>\n\t<pageurl>'+this.qt+"</pageurl>\n\t<pagetitle>"+this.$t+"</pagetitle>\n\t<pagetext>"+this.dt+"</pagetext>\n\t<additionalContext>"+this.Xt+"</additionalContext>\n\t</input>\n\t# Output:\n\t",hydePrompt:'<context>\nThe user is reading an email thread and needs one time-saving web-automation suggestion that completes the next substantive workflow step.\nIgnore purely email-centric actions (reply, forward, label, archive, mark as read, summarize, etc.).\nBase every decision only on the email\'s content, not the email client.\n</context>\n<instructions>\nStep 1 – Extract Candidate Tasks\n  a. Carefully read the entire email thread.\n  b. List every explicit or strongly implied web-based or workflow task (payments, approvals, registrations, calendar events, document signing, password resets, etc.).\n\nStep 2 – Rank Tasks\n  Rank the tasks by how much they advance the underlying workflow (highest impact first). Prioritise tasks with:\n    • A primary button, link, or clear call-to-action.\n    • Deadlines, due dates, or urgency language.\n    • Dependency by other people or later steps.\n\nStep 3 – Select the Top Task\n  Choose the single highest-ranked task that is NOT a trivial email operation.\n\nStep 4 – Draft the Automation Title\n  a. Start with one imperative verb in its base form (Pay, Add, Approve, Reset, Sign, Track, View, Complete, Submit, Schedule, Update, Award, etc.).\n  b. Follow with the longest distinctive noun phrase that uniquely identifies the task, copied exactly (verbatim, same word order and spelling) from the email—including brand names, survey titles, form codes, event names, etc.\n  c. You may insert short prepositions (to, in, for) ONLY when absolutely required for clarity.\n  d. Maximum 6 words total. Use Title Case (Capitalize Each Major Word). No punctuation other than spaces.\n\nStep 5 – Self-Audit for Specificity & Naming\n  • Confirm the noun phrase appears in the email text exactly as written.\n  • Confirm important qualifiers (company, product, document code) are included.\n  • If either check fails, revise the title before continuing.\n\nStep 6 – Output\n  Output ONLY the title inside the exact XML tag below and nothing else.\n\n<output_format>\n<automation_title>{Imperative Verb + Exact Noun Phrase}</automation_title>\n</output_format>\n</instructions>\n<examples>\n  <example>\n    Email Excerpt: "Please settle invoice #4431 for PixelPrint by Friday."\n    Expected Output: <automation_title>Pay Invoice #4431 For PixelPrint</automation_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Email Excerpt: "Click the button below to add the \'Kickoff Meeting\' to your calendar."\n    Expected Output: <automation_title>Add Kickoff Meeting To Calendar</automation_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Email Excerpt: "Your password for Acme Portal has expired. Reset it now to regain access."\n    Expected Output: <automation_title>Reset Acme Portal Password</automation_title>\n  </example>\n</examples>\n\t<input>\n\t<pageurl>'+this.qt+"</pageurl>\n\t<pagetitle>"+this.$t+"</pagetitle>\n\t<emailThread>"+this.dt+"</emailThread>\n\t</input>\n\t# Output:\n\t",skillRecommendationPrompt:"<instructions>\n\tYour task is to determine whether any of the provided skills in the '<available_skills>' tag are suitable for the user's current context on the web page (i.e., what the user is currently viewing or doing on the web page). The web page context is presented in the '<webpage_context>' tag.\n\t\n\tSpecifically, think through this skill determination step by step:\n\t\n\t#Step 1 - Evaluate all skills and rank them by fit:\n\t- Review all the available skills and compare each one to the user's situation provided in the '<webpage_context>' tag.\n\t- Determine how well each skill matches what the user is most likely trying to do or will want to do next.\n\t- Produce a ranking of skills based on best fit.\n\t\n\t#Step 2 – Filter for true relevance:\n\tFor each skill (in order of fit), check:\n\t- If the skill does not clearly help the user take action, complete a task, or continue a process that is clearly implied in the <webpage_context> — exclude it.\n\t- If the skill was not clearly built for this type of scenario — exclude it. It must feel like: \"this is exactly the kind of moment this skill was designed for.\"\n\t- If the skill is triggered by a keyword or phrase that is merely listed, linked, or previewed on the page — such as an email subject line, item in a dashboard, or task in a feed — and not something the user is directly focused on — exclude it.\n\t- If the <webpage_context> mentions the name of an app, platform, site, service, or form — and that name does **not** appear in the skill’s name or description — exclude it.\n\t\n\t#Step 3 — Final selection:\n\t- From the remaining valid skills, return up to the top 3 skills (most fitting first).\n\t- If no skills pass all relevance filters — return [0].\n\t- If only 1 or 2 skills pass — return a list containing only those skills.\n\t- If 3 or more skills pass — return a list with the top 3.\n\t\n\t<expected_output_format>\n\tReturn a list of integers representing the selected skills, ordered by best fit. Examples:\n\t- No relevant skills → [0]\n\t- One relevant skill → [3]\n\t- Two relevant skills → [3, 5]\n\t- Three or more relevant skills → [3, 5, 2]\n\tReturn only the list, without explanation, title, or formatting.\n\t</expected_output_format>\n</instructions>\n\t",groupNamingPrompt:'<instructions>\nYou are naming a UI button that represents a collapsible group of up to 3 suggested skills (automatic actions).\nGiven the list of skills <skills>, Your task is pick the *smallest common scope* (tightest shared concept) that truthfully covers ALL skills in the group.\nIf the skills don’t share a tight scope, broaden to the nearest umbrella that still honestly covers everything.\nThink in terms of a hierarchy: specific topic → broader topic → broadest helpful umbrella.\nYou are NOT describing each skill; you are labeling the group with a single shared scope.\n\nRules:\n- Output must be 2–4 words total.\n- Must end with the word "assistance".\n- Use Title Case for all words (e.g., "Time Off assistance").\n- Do NOT use "&", "/", commas, or parentheses.\n- Do NOT include verbs like View/Update/Approve/Change/Create/Delete/Request.\n- Prefer a specific scope when possible; only broaden when needed.\n- If one skill is an outlier, broaden enough to include it, but avoid over-broad names.\n\nHow to choose scope (examples of broadening):\n- If all skills are about the same object/topic, name that topic:\n  ["View goals","Update goal"] → "Goal assistance"\n- If skills share a parent concept, use the parent:\n  ["View goals","Update goal","Request feedback"] → "Performance assistance"\n- If the set spans different HR domains, widen to an HR umbrella:\n  ["View my enrolled benefits","Approve time off"] → "HR assistance"\n- If the set is very mixed and only clearly “employee tasks”, use the broadest safe umbrella:\n  ["View address","View compliance tasks","Approve employee central workflow requests"] → "Employee assistance"\n<output_format>\n  <skill_group_title>{Title Case Scope + "assistance"}</skill_group_title>\n</output_format>\n</instructions>\n<examples>\n  <example>\n    Skills: ["Create time off","View holiday calendar"]\n    Expected Output: <skill_group_title>Time Off assistance</skill_group_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Skills: ["Give feedback","Create spot award"]\n    Expected Output: <skill_group_title>Feedback assistance</skill_group_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Skills: ["View goals","Update goal"]\n    Expected Output: <skill_group_title>Goal assistance</skill_group_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Skills: ["View goals","Update goal","Request feedback"]\n    Expected Output: <skill_group_title>Performance assistance</skill_group_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Skills: ["View job relationships","Change job relationships","Delete job relationships"]\n    Expected Output: <skill_group_title>Org Structure assistance</skill_group_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Skills: ["Create or update auto delegation","View auto delegation","Approve employee central workflow requests"]\n    Expected Output: <skill_group_title>Workflow assistance</skill_group_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Skills: ["Give interview feedback","View target role","Change position"]\n    Expected Output: <skill_group_title>Career assistance</skill_group_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Skills: ["View my enrolled benefits","Approve time off"]\n    Expected Output: <skill_group_title>HR assistance</skill_group_title>\n  </example>\n  <example>\n    Skills: ["View address","View compliance tasks","Approve employee central workflow requests"]\n    Expected Output: 